# Session Changelog

At the **end of every session that produced any code change** (file edits, deletions, creations, commits, pushes, merges, deploys), the agent writes a single Markdown file at:

```
docs/sessions/YYYY-MM-DD-<kebab-slug>.md
```

`<kebab-slug>` is 3-6 words describing the session's main goal (`workers-cleanup-and-merge`, `figma-export-tooling`, `stripe-webhook-fix`).

## Required sections

```markdown
# <Session title>

**Date:** YYYY-MM-DD
**Branch(es):** main, sync/...
**Outcome:** done | partial | blocked
**Pushed to:** none | typekpaco | mtesting | both | <other>

## User request
One paragraph summarizing what the user actually asked for (not what we ended up doing).

## What changed
- `path/to/file` \u2014 created | modified | deleted | renamed \u2014 one-line reason
- (group related files)

## Decisions made
- Why X over Y (especially conflict resolutions, architecture picks, scope cuts)

## Commits
- `<short-sha>` <commit subject>

## Open follow-ups
- [ ] thing the user said "later"
- [ ] thing we noticed but didn't fix
- [ ] anything that needs human action before next session

## Notes for the next agent
Any context that won't be obvious from `git log` alone (env vars to set, services to restart, manual steps the user did, etc.).
```

## Rules

- **One file per session, not per task.** A session = the contiguous chat that ends here.
- **Write it as the last action.** Don't write it mid-session.
- **Don't duplicate `git log`.** The "What changed" section should explain *why*, not list every modified line.
- **Truthful.** If something was attempted and abandoned, say so under "Decisions made".
- **Skip if the session was purely Q&A** with no file edits.
- **Append, never rewrite.** If a session resumes the next day, create a new file dated for the resume; cross-reference the previous one.

## Reading past sessions

Future agents should skim `docs/sessions/` (newest first) before starting non-trivial work, to inherit context about recent decisions and open follow-ups.
